Phishing Detection & Awareness Report
1. Introduction

Phishing is a cyber-attack technique where attackers impersonate trusted organizations to trick users into revealing sensitive information such as login credentials, bank details, or OTPs. These attacks commonly occur through emails containing fake links, urgent messages, or malicious attachments.

2. Objective

The objective of this task is to:

Detect and analyze phishing emails

Identify key phishing indicators

Classify emails based on risk

Educate users using simple, business-friendly explanations

Provide effective prevention and awareness guidelines

3. Tools Used

Public phishing email samples

Email header analysis tools

Web browser (link and domain inspection)

Google Docs / MS Word (documentation)

4. Methodology

Each email was analyzed using the following approach:

Sender email and domain verification

Link inspection without clicking

Identification of urgency or fear-based language

Detection of spoofed branding or fake websites
5. Common Phishing Techniques Identified

Email spoofing using similar-looking domains

Fake login or verification pages

Urgency and fear-based messaging

Impersonation of banks, delivery services, or IT teams

Malicious attachments disguised as invoices or documents

6. Prevention & Awareness Guidelines

Always verify sender email domains carefully

Do not click links from unexpected or urgent emails

Never share passwords, OTPs, or banking details via email

Hover over links to check destination before clicking

Report suspicious emails to the IT or security team

Use spam filters and updated security software

7. Conclusion

Phishing remains one of the most common and effective cyber-attack methods due to human error. By identifying phishing indicators and spreading awareness, organizations and individuals can significantly reduce the risk of data breaches and financial fraud. User education is the strongest defense against phishing attacks.

